function pageuibasics$1Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"next`\n\
\n\ \n\
UI – Windows
\n\ \n\ The main tools you will interact with in this environment are windows, menus, and filterable lists.\n\ \n\ Windows are compound objects that usually encapsulate one tool. They can be `hover-video:\"collapsed and expanded\" 'cloxp/videos/win-col-expand', pt(300, 157)`, `hover-video:\"dragged around\" 'cloxp/videos/win-drag', pt(300, 157)`, `hover-video:\"resized\" 'cloxp/videos/win-resize', pt(300, 157)`, and `hover-video:\"aligned\" 'cloxp/videos/win-align', pt(542, 306)`.\n\ \n\ One window at a time can be active. An active window receives keyboard events and delegates those to some object inside it. Often you work with multiple windows / tools at once. To quickly switch between them `hover-video:\"you can use a keyboard shortcut\" 'cloxp/videos/window-nav', pt(500, 257)` *alt-`* (that is alt-backtick) or use the `doit:\"window menu bar entry\" this.acShowWindowMenuBarEntry();`."; }

229.source:
function pageuibasics$2Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"next`\n\
\n\ \n\
UI – Menus
\n\ \n\ Menus provide access to actions in a certain context.\n\ \n\ - __Menu bar__ The entries found in the `doit:\"menu bar\" showMarkerFor($morph(/MenuBar/));` give you access to globally available tools and actions.\n\ - The `doit:\"open\" showMarkerFor($morph(/clojureToolsLabel/));` entry allows to open Clojure workspaces, and System browsers, as well as Clojars browsers.\n\ - With the `doit:\"Clojure connection indicator\" showMarkerFor($morph(/clojureStatusLabel/));` you can start / stop / connect to Clojure servers and open a repl log that can be useful for debugging.\n\ - The `doit:\"file system entry\" showMarkerFor($morph(/cwdLabel/));` can be used to change the current directory (most often this will be the directory the project you are working on is located in) and open file system related tools.\n\ - In case something goes wrong in cloxp itself you might want to check the The `doit:\"system internal logs\" showMarkerFor($morph(/LogMenuBarEntry/));`. If you encountered a but, please `doit:\"file a bug report\" this.acShowHowToFileABugReport();`. Thank you!\n\ \n\ - __`hover-video:\"Code editor menu\" 'cloxp/videos/codeeditor-menu', pt(330, 170)`:__ Actions to browse, modify, evaluate code objects are included here. You also get access to settings such as shortcut bindings.\n\ \n\ - __`hover-video:\"System browser menu\" 'cloxp/videos/browser-menu', pt(500, 400)`:__ Actions related to general browser behavior and selected items. The list and codeeditor views of the browser each provide context specifix actions.\n\ \n\ Other objects may provide additional actions and menus.\n\ "; }

232.source:
function pageuibasics$3Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `doit:\"next\"`\n\
\n\ \n\
UI – Selection lists
\n\ \n\ One repeating pattern when interacting with cloxp is the selection of items. Be it for switching windows, code completion, or selecting a search result, often a large list of options need to be searched and one selected.\n\ \n\ Cloxp provides selection narrowers for this task. A narrower is a screen-sized list with an input element at the bottom. You can filter content by typing substrings into it. You usually can enter multiple, space separated substrings to filter all items containing *both* terms.\n\ \n\ `doit:\"Click here\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/sys-browser-narrow', true, this.getExtent());` to see how to search for all clojure symbols in namespaces ending with core and containing the string map.\n\ \n\ When the System Browse is active you can use `alt-t` to search for symbols."; }

250.source:
function pageclojuretools$1Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"next`\n\
\n\ \n\
Clojure Tools – Workspace
\n\ \n\ Workspaces are code editors that allow you to enter and evaluate Clojure code. They are useful if you need a \"scratch\" space, for example, to try out code snippets or to inspect objects. `doit:\"Give me a demo!\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/cloxp-eval', true, this.getExtent());`\n\ \n\ To evaluate an expression, either select it entirely or move the cursor behind it. Then press `alt-enter`. The evaluation result will appear in a box at the bottom. you can then either `hover-video:\"insert the evaluation result in the workspace, open another workspace with it\" 'cloxp/videos/cloxp-eval-insert-open', pt(608, 310)`, or just continue working.\n\ \n\ Unless specifically set via a `ns` or `in-ns` form, workspaces will evaluate code in the _user_ namespace."; }

253.source:
function pageclojuretools$2Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"next`\n\
\n\ \n\
Clojure Tools – System Browser
\n\ \n\
\n\ \n\

The system browser is the main tool for exploring and authoring clojure code. The browser can be opened from `doit:\"the tools menu bar entry\" this.acShowHowToOpenCljSystemBrowser();`.

\n\ \n\

Hover over the marked fields to see a description for the individual browser controls.

\n\ \n\

See the `link:\"how to create a new project\"'projects',1` and `link:\"how to add an existing project\"'projects',2` for how to use the browser in the context of your own projects.

\n\ \n\
\n\ \n\ `morph: this.morphSystemBrowserDoc();`\n\ "; }

256.source:
function pageclojuretools$3Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `doit:\"next\"`\n\
\n\ \n\
Clojure Tools – Clojars Browser
\n\ \n\ The `doit:\"clojars browser\" this.acShowHowToOpenCljClojarsBrowser();` allows to search the [clojars.org](https://clojars.org/) repository and to install and load libraries on the fly.\n\ \n\ When you a package gets installed and the `doit:\"currently selected directory\" showMarkerFor($morph('cwdLabel'))` includes a `pom.xml` or `project.clj` configuration file you will be asked if the package should be added as a dependency.\n\ \n\ Also, once installed you will be asked to load the namespaces provided by the package into the runtime.\n\ \n\ *Please note:* Due to [technical limitations of how JVM classloaders work](https://github.com/cemerick/pomegranate#add-classpath-usage), it is sometimes not possible to load all dependencies at runtime correctly. In case you experience problems, please restart the repl server, the dependencies will be correctly installed at startup.\n\ \n\ Note: right now packages won't be loaded (required) and added to pom.xml/project.clj automatically. This feature will come with the next release"; }

259.source:
function pageparedit$1Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `doit:\"next\"`\n\
\n\ \n\
Paredit
\n\ \n\ By default, clojure text editors have _paredit_ enabled. Paredit uses an AST behind the scene to allow structural editing operations. If you don't want it, you can disable paredit anytime via the `hover-video:\"context menu of editors\" 'cloxp/videos/paredit-disable', pt(450,260)`.\n\ \n\ action | shortcut | what it does\n\ -----|--------|-----------\n\ open list | `(` and `[` and `{` | `a⫿aa⇒a(⫿)aa`\n\ close list | `)` and `]` and `}` | `(a⫿aa)⇒(aaa)⫿`\n\ wrap around | `alt-(` and `alt-[` and `alt-{` | `a⫿aa⇒a(⫿aa)`\n\ \"slurp\" | `ctrl-shift-(` and `ctrl-shift-)` | `a (bb ⫿cc)⇒(a bb ⫿cc)` and `(bb ⫿cc) aa⇒(bb ⫿cc aa)`\n\ \"barf\" | `ctrl-shift-]` and `ctrl-shift-[` | `(a bb ⫿cc)⇒a (bb ⫿cc)` and `(bb ⫿cc aa)⇒(bb ⫿cc) aa`\n\ delete | `backspace` and `delete` and `ctrl-d` | Based on where they will be invoked will delete expressions, chars or nothing\n\ delete expression | `ctrl-alt-k` and `ctrl-alt-backspace` | `a ⫿bb ccc⇒a ⫿ ccc`\n\ splice | `alt-s` | `(a ⫿bb)⇒a ⫿bb`\n\ splice delete | `alt-shift-up` and `alt-shift-down` | `(a ⫿bb)⇒⫿bb` and `(a ⫿bb)⇒a⫿`\n\ split | `alt-shift-s` | `(a ⫿bb)⇒(a) ⫿(bb)`\n\ transpose | `ctrl-alt-t` | `(a ⫿bb)⇒(bb ⫿a)`\n\ indent | `tab` | Indents line or selection.\n\ newline | `enter` | Inserts newline and indents.\n\ "; }

265.source:
function pageostools$1Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"next`\n\
\n\ \n\
Accessing files and directories
\n\ \n\ __File system access:__ The menu bar allows you to see `doit:\"the current working directory and gives access to file system related tools\" this.acShowCurrentDirectoryMenuBarEntry();`.\n\ \n\ All operating systems commands and commands involving files that are issued by cloxp happen in the context of the currently selected directory. If you want to work on a specific project you should set the current directory to the root path of this project so that when you start a server or run an operating system command like git it will happen inside this directory.\n\ \n\ Via the file system menu bar entry you can open a `doit:\"directory viewer\" this.acShowHowToOpenDirViewer();` to browse the file system and open files.\n\ \n\ __Searching for and in files:__ Searching `doit:\"for\" this.acShowHowToSearchForFiles();` and `doit:\"in\" this.acShowHowToSearchInFiles();` can be done from the directory menu entry as well.\n\ \n\ __Running shell commands:__ If you need to run additional programs such as git or other java processes you can start and control them from `doit:\"shell command lines\" this.acShowHowToOpenTerminal();`. Commands will run in the context of the currently selected directory.\n\ "; }

268.source:
function pageclojure_coding$1Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"'clojure_coding', 4`\n\
\n\ \n\
Evaluating Clojure code
\n\ \n\ All code editors showing Clojure code can evaluate expressions. This includes workspaces, code views in the System Browser, and text editors presenting clj files. Evaluation can be triggered via the context menu or key shortcuts. When evaluating code it matters _what is selected and where the cursor is placed_. If a selection exists, the code inside the selection is evaluated. Otherwise the evaluation target is the last expression to the left of the cursor.\n\ \n\ Additionally, when you modify top-level code such as function definitions, you can directly evaluate the entire top-level expression.\n\ \n\ Evaluation results (and errors) appear in a box at the bottom. If you want to use the evaluation result you can insert it into the current editor or open it in another.\n\ \n\ `Alt-Enter`: Evaluate selection or last expression.\n\ \n\ `Alt-Shift-Space`: Evaluate top-level expression.\n\ \n\ `Alt-Shift-Enter`: Insert eval result (or `link:\"inspect\"'clojure_coding', 2` when no result present).\n\ \n\ `Alt-o`: Open eval result in a new window.\n\ \n\ `doit:\"Give me a demo!\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/cloxp-eval', true, this.getExtent());`\n\ \n\ "; }

271.source:
function pageclojure_coding$2Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"'clojure_coding', 3`\n\
\n\ \n\
Print-Inspecting Clojure objects
\n\ \n\ Apart from normal evaluation that produces a simple `str` representation of the resulting object you can also pretty print (\"print inspect\") results.\n\ \n\ `Alt-Shift-Enter`: Print inspect.\n\ \n\ By default, a print depth of 6 will be used. You can determine the print depth by giving a count argument to the print inspect command. You do this by pressing `Ctrl-number` before the print inspect command. For example to print to depth 15 you would press `Ctrl-1 Ctrl-5 Alt-Shift-Enter`.\n\ \n\ When a result box is present you can press `Alt-Shift-Enter` again to insert it's text into the editor. Press `Alt-o` to open it in another editor.\n\ "; }

274.source:
function pageclojure_coding$3Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"'paredit', 1`\n\
\n\ \n\
Code completions
\n\ \n\ Cloxp provides context specific static and dynamic code completions. You can eiter invoke completions via the context menu or with:\n\ \n\ `Alt-Shift-p`: List completions.\n\ \n\ Here is how you work with it:\n\ \n\ - `hover-video:\"Completing functions\" 'cloxp/videos/compl-menu', pt(500, 278)`\n\ - `hover-video:\"Completing namespaces and namespace functions\" 'cloxp/videos/compl-shortcut', pt(500, 278)`\n\ - `hover-video:\"Property completion\" 'cloxp/videos/compl-properties', pt(520, 290)` (dynamic, requires eval, great to \"browse\" through object interfaces)"; }

277.source:
function pagegetstarted$1Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `doit:\"next\"`\n\
\n\ \n\
Getting Started
\n\ \n\ **Welcome to cloxp!** This section gives an overview of the tools and interactions you need to work with cloxp.\n\ First, please note that this help system includes links (underlined black), linked actions (`doit:\"green\" $world.inform('Hello :)')` ☜ click it), and hover actions (`hover-video:\"hover your mouse here\" 'cloxp/videos/cloxp-rotating', pt(200, 190)`) that will be used for actively explaining cloxp.\n\ \n\ **Windows.** Cloxp has a windowing system that allows to open and arrange tools as you need them. The cloxp help window that you are looking at now is an example, you can resize and reposition it as required. See the help section about `link:\"windows\"'uibasics',1` for more details. \n\ \n\ **Get Clojure running**\n\ \n\ 1. Start a server: The `doit:\"connection indicator\" this.showMarkerFor($morph(/clojureStatusLabel/))` in the menu bar shows if you are connected to a clojure server (green) or not (red). To start a server, click the `doit:\"start repl server menu entry\" this.acShowHowToStartServer();`.\n\ \n\ 2. Once the server is started (you can close its console view), open a `doit:\"Cojure workspace\" this.acShowHowToOpenCljWorkspace();`. In it you can `doit:\"evaluate code\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/cloxp-eval', true, this.getExtent());`. In case you are unfamiliar with _paredit_ you probably want to `link:\"read this\"'paredit',1`.\n\ \n\ 3. To browse the namespaces and functions of the Clojure runtime system, open a `doit:\"System Browser\" this.acShowHowToOpenCljSystemBrowser();`. It allows to see the loaded namespaces, modify them and their definitions, and create new namespaces.\n\ \n\ You can now create a new Clojure project or import existing ones into you workspace. See the `link:\"help overview\"'helpoverview',0` to learn more about the other tools and workflows."; }

304.source:
function pageclojure_coding$4Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"'clojure_coding', 5`\n\
\n\ \n\
Live eval
\n\ \n\ Cloxp is able to evaluate code as you type. To enable it you can turn on the live eval checkbox in the menu of every clojure editor.\n\ \n\
\n\ ![](cloxp/images/menu-live-eval.png?)\n\
\n\ \n\ `doit:\"Show screencast\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/live-eval-large', true, this.getExtent());`"; }

307.source:
function pageclojure_coding$5Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"'clojure_coding', 2`\n\
\n\ \n\
capture & debug
\n\ \n\ Expressions inside of named entities declared via _def_ can be instrumented to record values when those expressions are evaluated. This makes the insertion of _print_ statements unncessary. More important, captured values can be retrieved later and pragmatically inspected.\n\ \n\ You can evaluate captures in code editor menus.\n\ \n\
\n\ ![](cloxp/images/menu-capture.png)\n\
\n\ \n\ The `doit:\"screencast\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/cloxp-capture-doc', true, this.getExtent());` shows how this feature can be used and how to open the inspectors giving access to recorded values."; }

325.source:
function pageprojects$1Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"next`\n\
\n\ \n\
How to create a new project with cloxp
\n\ \n\ 1. If a directory for the project already exists: `doit:\"Set the current directory to the project directory\" this.showHowToChangeDir();`. Otherwise, `doit:\"open a directory browsers\" this.acShowHowToOpenDirViewer();`, create a new directory and set it as the working directory.\n\ \n\ 2. If necessary create a [`project.clj`](https://github.com/technomancy/leiningen#configuration) or `pom.xml` inside the new directory.\n\ \n\ 3. `hover-video:\"Start a repl server\" 'cloxp/videos/cloxp-start-repl-server', pt(608,310)`.\n\ \n\ 4. Open a system browser and add a new namespace.\n\ \n\ \n\ You can see the entire workflow `doit:\"here\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/create-a-new-project', true, this.getExtent());`.\n\ "; }

328.source:
function pageprojects$2Markdown(state) { return "
\n\ `link:\"back\"back`\n\ `link:\"next\"next`\n\
\n\ \n\
How to add an existing project to cloxp
\n\ \n\ 1. `doit:\"Set the current directory to the project directory\" this.showHowToChangeDir();`.\n\ \n\ 2. `hover-video:\"Start a repl server\" 'cloxp/videos/cloxp-start-repl-server', pt(608,310)`.\n\ \n\ 3. Open a system browser and load the namespaces required.\n\ \n\ \n\ You can see the entire workflow `doit:\"here\" this.wrappedVideoMorph('cloxp/videos/open-exisiting-project', true, this.getExtent());`.\n\ "; }
